				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">The NES only gives you 2 name tables, and that's usually enough to scroll horizontally and vertically as much as you want. You might end up with slight scrolling artifacts around the edges of the screen (e.g. look at the sides of the screen in SMB3 or Kirby's Adventure) depending on how bad you want to hide them, but it's definitely possible to avoid those (look at Jurassic Park, Felix the Cat and Alfred Chicken, for example). Another way to get clean 4-way scrolling is to use add extra RAM to the cartridge and use 4 name tables instead of 2, but not many games did that.<br /><br />Whatever the name table layout you choose, the basic idea is that you draw new parts of the level to areas in the name tables that aren't visible, effectively replacing the parts of the level that were already visited by the player with the parts he hasn't seen yet, right before they scroll into view. This is what tepples' animation is showing.<br /><br />In addition to overwriting the background progressively, you must give your sprites the ability to move in a space bigger than 256x240 pixels. This often means giving them 16-bit coordinates, instead of the newbie-friendly 8-bit. the hard part about this is that the NES can still only place sprites in a 256x240-pixel area, no matter how big your level is. The most professional solution here is to have 2 separate spaces: level space and screen space. Have the game objects move freely in level space using 16-bit coordinates, and convert those coordinates to 8-bit screen coordinates only when generating OAM data. This can be done by subtracting the camera's coordinates (which are also in level space) from the coordinates of the objects.<br /><br />Think about it: if an object is sitting at X coordinate 384, it's in the middle of the second screen of the level. If the camera is at coordinate 0, the object should be completely hidden, because only the first screen is visible. 384 - 0 = 384, which is way past the 256 pixels of an NES screen. As the camera moves right, the distance between it and the object decreases, until that difference less than 256, at which point the object will become visible at the far right of the screen. Once the camera reaches X coordinate 256 (i.e. perfectly aligned to the second screen of the level), 384 - 256 = 128, which is precisely the middle of the screen.<br /><br />It's not such a complex concept once you understand that the NES can only represent a limited space, but with some math you can turn that small space into a &quot;window&quot; that scrolls over a much larger area. That math is basically the conversion between level space and screen/name table space.<br /><br />Of course there are other things to take into consideration, such as spawning enemies (you can't have all the objects of a big level active at all times, there's no memory or CPU for that), but ou shouldn't worry about that until you get the scrolling working.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

