				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">If the player is more than 128 pixels to the right of the camera, run your camera move code. Otherwise, don't.</div><br />Keeping the player perfectly centered at all times may feel a bit stiff sometimes. An alternative is to implement a small window (even 32 pixels wide is better) where the player can move without causing the screen to scroll.<br /><br />The basic idea is that the camera follows the player. Like any other game object, the camera should have an AI routine, and in this routine you put the logic that follows the player. The AI for a camera can be very simple: If the player is outside of the window, move the camera (and the window) in the direction that will put the player back in the window. Also check for the boundaries of the level, to prevent the camera from going beyond them.<br /><br />Another good thing about using a window is that you can move this window within the screen, so that when the player is moving right, you can move the window to the left and increase visibility on the right, giving the player more time to react to enemies and obstacles. Once the player stops moving the window goes back to the center.<br /><br />These are just suggestions to improve the behavior of the camera and give players a more dynamic experience, but tepples' suggestion is indeed the most basic thing you can do to get the camera to follow the player.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

